00:01:18.510 --> 00:01:21.680
And I want to start with
a story that I heard

00:01:21.680 --> 00:01:24.740
and I was told by, going
back to the restaurant,

00:01:24.740 --> 00:01:28.430
by the person who works at
this three Michelin star

00:01:28.430 --> 00:01:29.300
restaurant in Italy.

00:01:29.300 --> 00:01:31.070
It's called Osteria Francescana.

00:01:31.070 --> 00:01:33.410
They are in Modena.

00:01:33.410 --> 00:01:35.960
And his name is
Giuseppe Palmieri.

00:01:35.960 --> 00:01:39.860
And this is actually the
story of a family of four

00:01:39.860 --> 00:01:42.190
who visited the restaurant
on a Friday night.

00:01:42.190 --> 00:01:44.810
So imagine a father, a
mother, an eight-year-old boy,

00:01:44.810 --> 00:01:46.640
and a 14-year-old boy.

00:01:46.640 --> 00:01:49.400
And Palmieri helps
them find their table,

00:01:49.400 --> 00:01:52.310
and then shows up
to take the order.

00:01:52.310 --> 00:01:53.960
And the father,
incredibly happy,

00:01:53.960 --> 00:01:57.740
makes an order for each
one of the four of them

00:01:57.740 --> 00:02:01.910
for a tasting menu
that has 13 dishes

00:02:01.910 --> 00:02:03.650
and is called Sensations.

00:02:03.650 --> 00:02:05.150
And it's almost
lunchtime, so I want

00:02:05.150 --> 00:02:07.700
to give you a sense
of the type of dishes

00:02:07.700 --> 00:02:09.150
that are part of this menu.

00:02:09.150 --> 00:02:12.020
So quite creative in the
way they're assembled.

00:02:12.020 --> 00:02:13.550
That's eel.

00:02:13.550 --> 00:02:19.490
Another dish that is part of
this 13 course tasting menu

00:02:19.490 --> 00:02:20.960
is the one that you see here.

00:02:20.960 --> 00:02:24.520
It looks like a funny ice
cream, but that's foie gras.

00:02:24.520 --> 00:02:29.210
So not the type of dishes the
growing boys would hunger for.

00:02:29.210 --> 00:02:31.730
Now, the father was so eager
to eat at the restaurant

00:02:31.730 --> 00:02:34.370
that not only made the
reservations for Friday night,

00:02:34.370 --> 00:02:36.740
he also made the reservations
for Saturday night.

00:02:36.740 --> 00:02:39.050
So it's now 24 hours later.

00:02:39.050 --> 00:02:42.170
The same family is
back at the restaurant.

00:02:42.170 --> 00:02:46.400
And Palmieri again welcomes them
in, brings them to their table,

00:02:46.400 --> 00:02:48.860
and then shows up
to take the order.

00:02:48.860 --> 00:02:52.060
This time, again very
happily, the father goes

00:02:52.060 --> 00:02:55.940
for a 10-course tasting
menu called the Tradition

00:02:55.940 --> 00:02:56.842
in Evolution.

00:02:56.842 --> 00:02:59.300
And again, I want to give you
a sense of the type of dishes

00:02:59.300 --> 00:03:00.590
that are part of the menu.

00:03:00.590 --> 00:03:04.100
One of them is called
snails under the earth.

00:03:04.100 --> 00:03:06.620
It's served as a soup,
but there actually

00:03:06.620 --> 00:03:08.720
is snails at the
bottom of the plate.

00:03:08.720 --> 00:03:12.770
And they're hidden under a
foam of raw garlic and potato.

00:03:12.770 --> 00:03:16.610
And the earth part of the
dish stands for black truffle,

00:03:16.610 --> 00:03:18.440
coffee, and nuts.

00:03:18.440 --> 00:03:20.780
Now, when Palmieri
was taking the order,

00:03:20.780 --> 00:03:26.450
he noticed that the boys almost
had a face of desperation,

00:03:26.450 --> 00:03:29.720
as if they were not
sharing the eagerness

00:03:29.720 --> 00:03:33.140
and excitement of their father
to have another gourmet meal.

00:03:33.140 --> 00:03:35.680
And the boys were keeping
quiet, but Palmieri

00:03:35.680 --> 00:03:37.580
turned to the
eight-year-old at the table

00:03:37.580 --> 00:03:41.110
and said, what would
you like to have?

00:03:41.110 --> 00:03:44.560
Pizza, said the
eight-year-old boy.

00:03:44.560 --> 00:03:47.030
Now, Osteria Francescana
is no pizzeria.

00:03:47.030 --> 00:03:49.970
There is no way you could
find pizza on their menu.

00:03:49.970 --> 00:03:51.890
And it's a rather serious place.

00:03:51.890 --> 00:03:54.920
Fresh flowers are brought
into the restaurant every day.

00:03:54.920 --> 00:03:58.910
The tables are put together
with surgical precision.

00:03:58.910 --> 00:04:03.290
The dishes are arranged with
a lot of attention to detail.

00:04:03.290 --> 00:04:06.680
And this is a restaurant that,
back in 2016, became the best

00:04:06.680 --> 00:04:08.070
restaurant in the world.

00:04:08.070 --> 00:04:10.820
And in fact, also
this year, in 2018,

00:04:10.820 --> 00:04:13.010
they were back at
the top of the list.

00:04:13.010 --> 00:04:17.389
But despite all of that,
when Palmieri heard pizza,

00:04:17.389 --> 00:04:20.660
he excused himself,
ran to the phone,

00:04:20.660 --> 00:04:24.560
called up the best pizzeria in
Modena, and ordered the pizza.

00:04:24.560 --> 00:04:29.390
And sure enough, about 15,
20 minutes later, a pizza

00:04:29.390 --> 00:04:32.600
showed up at the door
in a taxi, and pizza

00:04:32.600 --> 00:04:35.027
was served to the boys.

00:04:35.027 --> 00:04:36.860
Now, I'm telling you
this story because it's

00:04:36.860 --> 00:04:40.580
a perfect example of what
rebel talent is all about.

00:04:40.580 --> 00:04:43.100
Even in situations where
there are lots of rules,

00:04:43.100 --> 00:04:45.380
as in the case of
fancy restaurant,

00:04:45.380 --> 00:04:47.810
Palmieri was able to
keep his mind open,

00:04:47.810 --> 00:04:50.150
look at the problem from
a different perspective,

00:04:50.150 --> 00:04:52.710
and come up with a
rather creative solution.

00:04:52.710 --> 00:04:55.700
So what I want to suggest
is that we all probably want

00:04:55.700 --> 00:04:57.140
to be people like Palmieri.

00:04:57.140 --> 00:05:00.680
If we think about our
leadership, broadly defined,

00:05:00.680 --> 00:05:04.620
the people that we influence in
our different spheres of life,

00:05:04.620 --> 00:05:07.250
whether at work or
in our personal life,

00:05:07.250 --> 00:05:10.430
I would say that we
want to have people

00:05:10.430 --> 00:05:13.130
who would order the
pizza like Palmieri

00:05:13.130 --> 00:05:15.900
did in that particular instance.

00:05:15.900 --> 00:05:18.180
Now, what's interesting is
that I would call Palmieri

00:05:18.180 --> 00:05:22.130
a rebel for this behavior, for
many other behaviors that he

00:05:22.130 --> 00:05:25.560
engages in on a regular
basis in his work,

00:05:25.560 --> 00:05:28.520
but rebels usually
have a bad reputation.

00:05:28.520 --> 00:05:30.260
I spend a lot of time
in organizations,

00:05:30.260 --> 00:05:33.540
and I've collected all
sorts of words for them.

00:05:33.540 --> 00:05:36.140
They're called the show offs.

00:05:36.140 --> 00:05:39.230
Sometimes they're called the
jerks, or the annoying people

00:05:39.230 --> 00:05:42.670
who slow you down in your
decision-making processes.

00:05:42.670 --> 00:05:45.280
The troublemakers, the outcasts.

00:05:45.280 --> 00:05:50.350
In fact, I think that we
often have a very precise idea

00:05:50.350 --> 00:05:52.210
of the rebels in the business.

00:05:52.210 --> 00:05:55.900
We think about people like
Apple visionary Steve Jobs.

00:05:55.900 --> 00:05:59.290
So people who are incredibly
innovative and creative, but--

00:05:59.290 --> 00:06:01.180
at least the stories
go-- not the type

00:06:01.180 --> 00:06:03.760
of people you want to work
with, or have as a boss

00:06:03.760 --> 00:06:04.807
or as an employee.

00:06:04.807 --> 00:06:07.140
And what I want to do in the
time that we have together,

00:06:07.140 --> 00:06:09.223
and it was a big motivation
for writing this book,

00:06:09.223 --> 00:06:12.040
is try to shift that
thinking, and suggest

00:06:12.040 --> 00:06:15.580
that people who I call rebels
are not people who break rules

00:06:15.580 --> 00:06:17.570
just for the sake
of breaking rules,

00:06:17.570 --> 00:06:19.860
they are not people
who are arrogant,

00:06:19.860 --> 00:06:23.410
they are people who break rules
who hold them and others back.

00:06:23.410 --> 00:06:25.120
And they break
rules in a way that

00:06:25.120 --> 00:06:27.550
is very constructive
and productive

00:06:27.550 --> 00:06:30.065
and positive for
their organizations.

00:06:30.065 --> 00:06:32.890
So with that said, let me
share a few stories that

00:06:32.890 --> 00:06:34.720
are going to allow
us to talk about what

00:06:34.720 --> 00:06:37.374
are the ingredients
of their success.

00:06:37.374 --> 00:06:39.040
And the first story
that I want to share

00:06:39.040 --> 00:06:41.410
comes from the domain of sport.

00:06:41.410 --> 00:06:43.810
Now, some of you
might know this guy

00:06:43.810 --> 00:06:46.780
is a rather well-known coach.

00:06:46.780 --> 00:06:48.720
His name is Maurice Cheeks.

00:06:48.720 --> 00:06:51.490
And I want to tell you in
particular about the evening

00:06:51.490 --> 00:06:54.400
of April 23, 2003.

00:06:54.400 --> 00:06:56.110
This was a big night for him.

00:06:56.110 --> 00:06:59.650
It was game three of the
first round of the 2003 NBA

00:06:59.650 --> 00:07:00.970
championships.

00:07:00.970 --> 00:07:03.700
And I'd like you to
imagine being there.

00:07:03.700 --> 00:07:05.570
You're in a very big arena.

00:07:05.570 --> 00:07:09.250
20,000 fans ready
to watch the game.

00:07:09.250 --> 00:07:12.520
You're there with them, ready to
cheer up your team to success.

00:07:12.520 --> 00:07:15.610
Millions of viewers from home.

00:07:15.610 --> 00:07:19.860
And before the game
started, a girl

00:07:19.860 --> 00:07:23.860
who is about 14
years in age stepped

00:07:23.860 --> 00:07:27.400
into the arena ready to
sing the national anthem.

00:07:27.400 --> 00:07:30.340
And what I'd like you to
do is watch a video clip

00:07:30.340 --> 00:07:32.620
that I brought with
me of that moment.

00:07:32.620 --> 00:07:34.120
And I'd like you
to pay attention

00:07:34.120 --> 00:07:35.695
to what this coach does.

00:07:36.880 --> 00:07:38.600
Why don't we do the following?

00:07:38.600 --> 00:07:40.760
We'll come back to that.

00:07:40.760 --> 00:07:44.130
And I'm going to talk about
a different ingredient first,

00:07:44.130 --> 00:07:48.190
where we don't need to look
at the video quite yet.

00:07:48.190 --> 00:07:50.590
The second ingredient
that seems to be something

00:07:50.590 --> 00:07:56.050
the rebels do quite well
is having a great desire

00:07:56.050 --> 00:07:58.127
for challenge and for novelty.

00:07:58.127 --> 00:08:00.460
And I wanted to introduce
this ingredient by telling you

00:08:00.460 --> 00:08:02.180
about a personal story.

00:08:02.180 --> 00:08:06.260
It is Christmas time a few
years back at our house.

00:08:06.260 --> 00:08:13.380
And this is not
what happened there.

00:08:13.380 --> 00:08:17.957
I had what I thought was the
perfect gift for my husband.

00:08:17.957 --> 00:08:20.040
And the only thing that
you need to know about him

00:08:20.040 --> 00:08:21.748
is that he's the type
of person who would

00:08:21.748 --> 00:08:25.020
be super-happy to work here.

00:08:25.020 --> 00:08:26.280
So he's a complete geek.

00:08:26.280 --> 00:08:31.350
So always loves the new piece of
technology, the latest gadget.

00:08:31.350 --> 00:08:34.380
Everything that is
interesting and playful

00:08:34.380 --> 00:08:37.140
when it comes to technology
is the perfect gift for him.

00:08:37.140 --> 00:08:39.840
And so on Christmas
day, he runs downstairs.

00:08:39.840 --> 00:08:41.820
There is a big tree
in the living room.

00:08:41.820 --> 00:08:44.700
And under the tree,
he finds a big box

00:08:44.700 --> 00:08:46.530
that I prepared for him.

00:08:46.530 --> 00:08:48.330
And he takes the top off.

00:08:48.330 --> 00:08:52.530
And then he starts taking some
pieces of paper out of the box.

00:08:52.530 --> 00:08:55.470
There was this card at the
bottom of the box letting

00:08:55.470 --> 00:08:58.680
you know that they signed us up
for a 10-week, two-hour a week

00:08:58.680 --> 00:09:02.260
course in improv comedy.

00:09:02.260 --> 00:09:04.350
Now as it turns
out, improv comedy

00:09:04.350 --> 00:09:06.420
taught me all sorts of
interesting things that

00:09:06.420 --> 00:09:10.199
are really good lessons for
life in thinking about the work

00:09:10.199 --> 00:09:12.740
that we do and thinking about
the relationships that we have.

00:09:12.740 --> 00:09:17.820
And in the spirit of
bringing to bear something

00:09:17.820 --> 00:09:19.950
that I've learned by
taking this class,

00:09:19.950 --> 00:09:22.560
I thought that we could
do an exercise together

00:09:22.560 --> 00:09:24.870
that is one of the
exercise that we did quite

00:09:24.870 --> 00:09:27.610
a few times throughout improv.

00:09:27.610 --> 00:09:30.450
Now just to close
the story, my husband

00:09:30.450 --> 00:09:33.200
wasn't too happy when I
signed him up for this class.

00:09:33.200 --> 00:09:36.330
He really wanted the
latest gadget in his hands.

00:09:36.330 --> 00:09:38.710
But I thought he was wrong.

00:09:38.710 --> 00:09:41.700
And by the end of the
first two-hour class,

00:09:41.700 --> 00:09:44.340
he actually told me
that he hated it.

00:09:44.340 --> 00:09:47.370
But things started
to change as we

00:09:47.370 --> 00:09:50.070
went on and on for
our weekly classes.

00:09:50.070 --> 00:09:52.290
And he started really
enjoying having this date

00:09:52.290 --> 00:09:53.370
with the unexpected.

00:09:53.370 --> 00:09:55.495
So I'm going to ask each
of you, if you don't mind,

00:09:55.495 --> 00:09:58.080
to stand up for this exercise.

00:09:58.080 --> 00:10:00.660
I'm going to ask each of
you to find a partner.

00:10:00.660 --> 00:10:04.890
So a person who is
standing close to you

00:10:04.890 --> 00:10:07.020
that would work well.

00:10:07.020 --> 00:10:07.950
Perfect.

00:10:07.950 --> 00:10:13.590
And I'm going to put
myself up here so that you

00:10:13.590 --> 00:10:15.800
can see the directions.

00:10:15.800 --> 00:10:18.190
So this is not too difficult.

00:10:18.190 --> 00:10:22.200
OK I'm going to ask you to
stand about this distance

00:10:22.200 --> 00:10:22.965
from your partner.

00:10:26.990 --> 00:10:31.060
There is somebody over
here who needs a partner.

00:10:31.060 --> 00:10:34.082
Since you're working in pairs.

00:10:34.082 --> 00:10:36.540
And if you don't have a partner,
you can also work with me.

00:10:36.540 --> 00:10:37.940
I'm fine with that.

00:10:37.940 --> 00:10:38.440
OK.

00:10:38.440 --> 00:10:40.360
So here's what I'm
going to ask you to do.

00:10:40.360 --> 00:10:42.640
From that position, you're
going to be standing

00:10:42.640 --> 00:10:44.440
in front of your partner.

00:10:44.440 --> 00:10:46.750
I'm going to ask you to
spend the next 20 seconds--

00:10:46.750 --> 00:10:48.670
and I'm going to keep
the time for you--

00:10:48.670 --> 00:10:51.340
staring in the eyes
of your partner.

00:10:51.340 --> 00:10:52.560
OK?

00:10:52.560 --> 00:10:56.020
And there are a few more
rules before you get started.

00:10:56.020 --> 00:10:57.670
No laughing.

00:10:57.670 --> 00:10:59.260
No talking.

00:10:59.260 --> 00:11:00.550
No anything.

00:11:00.550 --> 00:11:04.030
No really expression of
any emotions on your face.

00:11:04.030 --> 00:11:04.570
OK?

00:11:04.570 --> 00:11:06.050
So that's the exercise.

00:11:06.050 --> 00:11:08.600
As I said, I'm going to
keep the time for you.

00:11:08.600 --> 00:11:10.675
And when there is
silence, you can start.

00:11:31.834 --> 00:11:32.815
And time.

00:11:35.740 --> 00:11:36.640
How did that feel?

00:11:36.640 --> 00:11:37.780
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:11:37.780 --> 00:11:38.738
AUDIENCE: It was great.

00:11:38.738 --> 00:11:40.152
FRANCESCA GINO: It was great?

00:11:40.152 --> 00:11:42.924
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:11:44.310 --> 00:11:46.936
Your face is like, meh.

00:11:46.936 --> 00:11:50.595
OK, for some of you,
maybe slightly awkward.

00:11:50.595 --> 00:11:55.890
A little bit weird,
uncomfortable.

00:11:55.890 --> 00:11:59.580
As it turns out, if you felt a
little bit awkward or slightly

00:11:59.580 --> 00:12:01.070
uncomfortable, that's OK.

00:12:01.070 --> 00:12:02.640
It means that you're human.

00:12:02.640 --> 00:12:05.250
Because our brain knows
that if we stand that close

00:12:05.250 --> 00:12:09.120
to a person looking in their
eyes for that amount of time,

00:12:09.120 --> 00:12:11.830
one or two things
usually happen.

00:12:11.830 --> 00:12:14.612
One, we're going
to kiss the person.

00:12:14.612 --> 00:12:16.620
Two, we're going to
punch them in the face.

00:12:16.620 --> 00:12:19.110
And I don't want any of
that to happen at Google.

00:12:19.110 --> 00:12:21.640
So you can go to your partner,
shake their hands and say,

00:12:21.640 --> 00:12:22.765
I'm not going to punch you.

00:12:22.765 --> 00:12:24.697
I'm not going to kiss you.

00:12:24.697 --> 00:12:28.550
OK, now that that
is out of the way--

00:12:28.550 --> 00:12:30.830
no, no, no, stand up.

00:12:30.830 --> 00:12:31.740
Not sitting yet.

00:12:31.740 --> 00:12:34.060
There is the second
part to the exercise.

00:12:34.060 --> 00:12:35.940
Now a beautiful
principle of improv

00:12:35.940 --> 00:12:39.660
is the idea of always working
on scenes with a partner

00:12:39.660 --> 00:12:42.210
and shifting the
attention from us to them.

00:12:42.210 --> 00:12:44.280
Our goal in scenes is
always trying our best

00:12:44.280 --> 00:12:47.100
to make our partner feel
good about what they're

00:12:47.100 --> 00:12:49.590
doing, or feeling as
confident as they can

00:12:49.590 --> 00:12:51.790
feel about what they're doing.

00:12:51.790 --> 00:12:54.480
And again, what a beautiful
lesson about life more

00:12:54.480 --> 00:12:55.031
generally.

00:12:55.031 --> 00:12:57.030
And so to practice that,
we are going to go back

00:12:57.030 --> 00:12:58.600
to the same position.

00:12:58.600 --> 00:13:03.210
Again, I'm going to ask you to
engage in this 20-second period

00:13:03.210 --> 00:13:04.720
of staring.

00:13:04.720 --> 00:13:07.620
But this time, you're also
trying to pay attention.

00:13:07.620 --> 00:13:10.380
So what is their eye color?

00:13:10.380 --> 00:13:12.990
Is their haircut
an interesting one?

00:13:12.990 --> 00:13:16.830
Or are there ears shaped in
a slightly different way?

00:13:16.830 --> 00:13:18.160
Whatever you want to do.

00:13:18.160 --> 00:13:20.254
You're trying to stare
but pay attention

00:13:20.254 --> 00:13:21.170
to what they're doing.

00:13:21.170 --> 00:13:22.140
OK?

00:13:22.140 --> 00:13:23.380
Same rules as before.

00:13:23.380 --> 00:13:28.300
So not talking, no laughing, no
facial expression of any kind.

00:13:28.300 --> 00:13:29.620
OK?

00:13:29.620 --> 00:13:30.850
Perfect.

00:13:30.850 --> 00:13:32.440
If you're ready, let's go.

00:13:46.020 --> 00:13:48.752
And time.

00:13:48.752 --> 00:13:49.640
OK.

00:13:49.640 --> 00:13:52.489
We're going to test whether you
were paying attention or not.

00:13:52.489 --> 00:13:53.030
AUDIENCE: Oh.

00:13:53.030 --> 00:13:54.738
FRANCESCA GINO: Seems
like that you were.

00:13:54.738 --> 00:13:55.700
I know, oh.

00:13:55.700 --> 00:13:57.950
That sounds like a
comment from my husband

00:13:57.950 --> 00:13:59.930
as we were going
through classes.

00:13:59.930 --> 00:14:03.050
You're going to turn
around 180 degrees.

00:14:03.050 --> 00:14:04.740
So each one of you.

00:14:04.740 --> 00:14:07.940
So this time it's not your
face looking at their face,

00:14:07.940 --> 00:14:10.160
but it's your back
looking at their back.

00:14:10.160 --> 00:14:11.590
Perfect.

00:14:11.590 --> 00:14:14.390
And what I'm going to ask you
to do is, each one of you,

00:14:14.390 --> 00:14:16.604
to think about two big changes.

00:14:16.604 --> 00:14:17.270
So I don't know.

00:14:17.270 --> 00:14:19.811
If you have glasses, you might
want to take your glasses off.

00:14:19.811 --> 00:14:21.260
Or rough up your hair.

00:14:21.260 --> 00:14:24.480
Be as creative as
you want to be.

00:14:24.480 --> 00:14:27.326
And then make those two
changes on yourself.

00:14:27.326 --> 00:14:27.826
OK?

00:14:32.590 --> 00:14:34.330
No taking off clothes.

00:14:34.330 --> 00:14:36.760
[LAUGHTER]

00:14:36.760 --> 00:14:40.410
Just-- perfect.

00:14:40.410 --> 00:14:41.030
OK.

00:14:41.030 --> 00:14:44.230
If you have your two
changes, when you're ready,

00:14:44.230 --> 00:14:45.570
you can turn around.

00:14:45.570 --> 00:14:48.270
And each of you can
guess the changes

00:14:48.270 --> 00:14:50.568
that you see in your partner.

00:14:50.568 --> 00:14:53.556
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:14:53.556 --> 00:14:56.544
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:15:23.143 --> 00:15:23.934
FRANCESCA GINO: OK.

00:15:30.450 --> 00:15:33.120
Were you able to
figure them out?

00:15:33.120 --> 00:15:33.620
Yeah?

00:15:39.332 --> 00:15:42.970
Again, it's quite nice
to be able to shift

00:15:42.970 --> 00:15:45.940
the attention from ourselves
to the other partner.

00:15:45.940 --> 00:15:50.680
So hopefully, most of you
were able to see the changes

00:15:50.680 --> 00:15:52.720
the other person actually made.

00:15:52.720 --> 00:15:55.390
Now I'm going to do a final
part of this exercise.

00:15:55.390 --> 00:15:56.980
And do we have music?

00:15:56.980 --> 00:15:58.190
Are we good with audio?

00:15:58.190 --> 00:15:58.690
Yeah?

00:15:58.690 --> 00:15:59.661
Perfect.

00:15:59.661 --> 00:16:00.160
OK.

00:16:00.160 --> 00:16:03.340
We're going to do the
final part of the exercise.

00:16:03.340 --> 00:16:05.860
And this is what I'm
going to ask you to do,

00:16:05.860 --> 00:16:08.890
if you don't mind.

00:16:08.890 --> 00:16:10.197
Do you like to dance?

00:16:10.197 --> 00:16:10.780
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:16:10.780 --> 00:16:11.613
FRANCESCA GINO: Yes.

00:16:11.613 --> 00:16:13.900
Oh, if I were to find
you on a dance floor,

00:16:13.900 --> 00:16:15.430
what would you be doing?

00:16:15.430 --> 00:16:16.480
AUDIENCE: Dancing.

00:16:16.480 --> 00:16:20.050
FRANCESCA GINO: Can you
show me one of your moves?

00:16:20.050 --> 00:16:20.850
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:16:20.850 --> 00:16:23.380
I generally have, like--

00:16:23.380 --> 00:16:25.406
and like--

00:16:25.406 --> 00:16:27.160
FRANCESCA GINO: OK.

00:16:27.160 --> 00:16:29.260
This is what I am seeing.

00:16:29.260 --> 00:16:31.590
So something along-- sorry.

00:16:31.590 --> 00:16:33.410
It's much better
than what I'm doing.

00:16:33.410 --> 00:16:34.240
But it's something around that.

00:16:34.240 --> 00:16:34.840
OK.

00:16:34.840 --> 00:16:38.020
So your role as-- and
again, each of you

00:16:38.020 --> 00:16:40.350
is going to do this in the pair.

00:16:40.350 --> 00:16:43.630
Each of you is going to think
about their favorite dance

00:16:43.630 --> 00:16:44.494
move.

00:16:44.494 --> 00:16:45.910
And I'm going to
put on some music

00:16:45.910 --> 00:16:49.275
and ask you to actually try it
out in front of your partner.

00:16:49.275 --> 00:16:51.400
And then you are going to
switch when I say switch.

00:16:51.400 --> 00:16:54.400
But here's the very important
role of the partner.

00:16:54.400 --> 00:16:57.940
Since your task is to make your
partner feel as good as they

00:16:57.940 --> 00:16:59.770
can feel about their dancing--

00:16:59.770 --> 00:17:01.720
in this case, or as
confident as they

00:17:01.720 --> 00:17:03.490
can feel about their dancing--

00:17:03.490 --> 00:17:06.880
you're mirroring,
but exaggerating.

00:17:06.880 --> 00:17:07.510
OK?

00:17:07.510 --> 00:17:09.335
So whatever it is.

00:17:09.335 --> 00:17:10.960
I don't know what I
would do this here.

00:17:10.960 --> 00:17:13.390
But in a way, that really makes
them feel good about the way

00:17:13.390 --> 00:17:14.109
they're dancing.

00:17:14.109 --> 00:17:14.952
OK?

00:17:14.952 --> 00:17:17.410
As I said, I'm going to put up
some music since it's easier

00:17:17.410 --> 00:17:18.369
to dance that way.

00:17:18.369 --> 00:17:20.635
You can decide who's
going to go first.

00:17:26.730 --> 00:17:32.572
And when you're ready, the
