00:18:29.460 --> 00:18:31.060
I'm very impressed.

00:18:31.060 --> 00:18:34.000
How did that feel compared
to the first exercise when

00:18:34.000 --> 00:18:35.920
you were staring?

00:18:35.920 --> 00:18:37.087
The first time you did that.

00:18:37.087 --> 00:18:38.003
AUDIENCE: Much better.

00:18:38.003 --> 00:18:39.530
FRANCESCA GINO:
Much better, right?

00:18:39.530 --> 00:18:42.270
It's interesting that
once we put ourselves

00:18:42.270 --> 00:18:44.770
out there in situations where
we feel challenged where we're

00:18:44.770 --> 00:18:47.710
always doing something
new, it becomes easier

00:18:47.710 --> 00:18:49.520
to feel comfortable
with the uncomfortable.

00:18:49.520 --> 00:18:51.670
That's what rebels often do.

00:18:51.670 --> 00:18:53.320
Now I was obviously
very interested

00:18:53.320 --> 00:18:56.240
in studying this idea in
the case of businesses.

00:18:56.240 --> 00:18:58.720
And so I went to
businesses to try

00:18:58.720 --> 00:19:00.850
to see how is it
that they injected

00:19:00.850 --> 00:19:03.640
this idea of challenge
and novelty in the work

00:19:03.640 --> 00:19:04.420
that people do.

00:19:04.420 --> 00:19:06.400
And one of the
businesses I visited,

00:19:06.400 --> 00:19:09.880
where I expected not to
find any rebelliousness,

00:19:09.880 --> 00:19:13.090
is a fast-food chain in the
middle of Tennessee and West

00:19:13.090 --> 00:19:13.734
Virginia.

00:19:13.734 --> 00:19:14.650
They looked like this.

00:19:14.650 --> 00:19:18.820
They are drive-through big
blue boxes with French fries

00:19:18.820 --> 00:19:20.725
and hot dogs on their roof.

00:19:20.725 --> 00:19:22.600
But they're quite
successful at what they do.

00:19:22.600 --> 00:19:25.360
In fact, if you look at
any measure of performance,

00:19:25.360 --> 00:19:26.950
revenue per square--

00:19:26.950 --> 00:19:29.980
you name it, they beat
the competition by far.

00:19:29.980 --> 00:19:32.740
And we're talking about big
brands like McDonald's, Burger

00:19:32.740 --> 00:19:34.590
King, Wendy's.

00:19:34.590 --> 00:19:38.030
Now they also invest in
people quite differently.

00:19:38.030 --> 00:19:41.500
So if at a place like
McDonald's you receive an hour

00:19:41.500 --> 00:19:44.020
and a half, two hours of
training per stations,

00:19:44.020 --> 00:19:49.360
at Pal's, they give you 135
hours of training per station.

00:19:49.360 --> 00:19:51.670
So they're really all about
making you an expert such

00:19:51.670 --> 00:19:55.180
that you have the free
space in your mind

00:19:55.180 --> 00:19:58.630
to think about how to improve
on the work that you do.

00:19:58.630 --> 00:20:02.200
Now when I was there, I was
in the middle of the store

00:20:02.200 --> 00:20:03.310
actually at rush hour.

00:20:03.310 --> 00:20:05.710
And so you see people
working at their stations

00:20:05.710 --> 00:20:07.664
almost like machines.

00:20:07.664 --> 00:20:09.580
And I started thinking
that maybe work becomes

00:20:09.580 --> 00:20:11.725
monotonous or even boring.

00:20:11.725 --> 00:20:14.830
And yet, the general managers
have thought about this.

00:20:14.830 --> 00:20:17.260
And so it's more ways
that they inject novelty.

00:20:17.260 --> 00:20:22.810
One way in which they do this
is the idea of letting people

00:20:22.810 --> 00:20:24.330
know the order
that they're going

00:20:24.330 --> 00:20:26.230
to follow throughout the day--

00:20:26.230 --> 00:20:29.590
the stations that
they're moving from, to--

00:20:29.590 --> 00:20:31.600
when they show up for work.

00:20:31.600 --> 00:20:34.090
So they create a little
bit of unpredictability,

00:20:34.090 --> 00:20:35.740
a little bit of
novelty that allows

00:20:35.740 --> 00:20:37.990
them to stay on their feet.

00:20:37.990 --> 00:20:39.675
And what's also
interesting is that they

00:20:39.675 --> 00:20:41.800
have all sorts of challenges
for the people working

00:20:41.800 --> 00:20:42.460
in the stores.

00:20:42.460 --> 00:20:44.860
My favorite to
date is a challenge

00:20:44.860 --> 00:20:47.170
for the person working
at the windows.

00:20:47.170 --> 00:20:48.960
So the person who
takes the order.

00:20:48.960 --> 00:20:52.750
An interesting statistic
about Pal's is that they

00:20:52.750 --> 00:20:54.230
have a lot of repeat customers.

00:20:54.230 --> 00:20:57.590
So people who eat there
five to six times a week.

00:20:57.590 --> 00:21:00.414
And they have a simple menu.

00:21:00.414 --> 00:21:02.080
And so people who are
creatures of habit

00:21:02.080 --> 00:21:04.850
tend to make the same order
whenever they show up.

00:21:04.850 --> 00:21:07.060
And so the challenge for
the person at the window

00:21:07.060 --> 00:21:11.110
was, if you can remember
100 orders in a row,

00:21:11.110 --> 00:21:12.534
then there is this reward.

00:21:12.534 --> 00:21:14.950
And it was really interesting
to see how the person really

00:21:14.950 --> 00:21:18.890
experienced it as being pushed
in the work that she did.

00:21:18.890 --> 00:21:21.370
And she was very happy
when she actually completed

00:21:21.370 --> 00:21:23.390
the challenge successfully.

00:21:23.390 --> 00:21:25.930
So what is very
true about rebels

00:21:25.930 --> 00:21:28.670
is that they have this
desire for novelty.

00:21:28.670 --> 00:21:31.660
They're not afraid of putting
themselves in situations

00:21:31.660 --> 00:21:33.760
that makes them uncomfortable.

00:21:33.760 --> 00:21:36.430
Now let's go back to the first
ingredient with the video

